\subsection{Expressions and values}

An expression |e| has syntax given in \Cref{fig:verse-syntax}.
Constants |k| are simply integers in this presentation, and come equipped with
some primitive operations |op|.  To avoid clutter, we provide only two representative
operations, |add^(e_1,e_2)| for integer addition, and |gt^(e_1,e_2)| for integer comparison.

\paragraph{Tuples and arrays.}
All functions (including |add| and |gt|) take a single argument, but that
argument can be a tuple, say |(e_1,e_2)|. In Verse, tuples and arrays are the same data structure;
a tuple is just an array whose size is statically known.
The expression |(e_1, dots, e_n)| builds an $n$-ary tuple, while |for| constructs an array.
We discuss |for| in \Cref{sec:for}.

\paragraph{Unification and sequencing.}
Unification |unify^(e_1,e_2)| and sequencing |semi^(e_1,e_2)| are two other primitive operations.
We often allow ourselves to write them with infix shorthand, |(e_1 == e_2)| and |(e_1; e_2)| respectively.

\paragraph{Lambda and application.}  Lambda abstractions are written |(x => e)|, and are applied
with the primitive operation |apply(e_1,e_2)|.

\paragraph{Choice.}
In Verse, an expression may yield a sequence of zero, one, or many results.  The expression |fail| yields
zero results; the expression |(e_1 choice e_2)| yields all the results of |e_1| and then all the results
of |e_2|.

\paragraph{Values.}
A value |v| can be a variable |x|, or it can be a head-normal form |hnf|.
The latter is just an integer constant |k|, an array |(v_1, dots,v_n)|, or a lambda |(x => e)|.

\subsection{\Hexp{}s and heaps}

A \hexp{} has the form |(def h in e)|, where |h| is a \emph{heap}, whose syntax is given in
\Cref{fig:verse-syntax}.  A heap is just a collection of \emph{bindings}, which take one of two forms:
\begin{itemize}
\item A binding |x| simply introduces the variable |x|, without giving it a value.
\item A binding |x:=v| binds the variable |x| to the value |v|.
\end{itemize}
These heaps play the role of |let| expressions in the call by need lambda calculus (\Cref{sec:call-by-need}).

A particular heap has at most one binding for a variable |x|.
When a heap is born, all its bindings are variable introductions |x|; as execution progresses some of
these variables get a value |x:=v|.  Once a variable gets value, that value never changes: it is immutable.

A binding in a heap may refer to another binding (e.g |x:=y| or |x:=(y,2)|); but the bindings are never recursive.
Here are some example heaps, with an indication of whether they are well formed:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{rl}
  Heap, $h$ & OK or not? \\
  \hline
  |(x:=1, y)| & OK \\
  |(x:=1, y:=2)| & OK \\
  |(x:=y, y:=2)| & OK \\
  |(x:=(1,x))|   & Not OK: recursive \\
  |(x:=(y1,y2), y1, y2:=4)| & OK \\
  |(x:=add^(1,2))| & Syntactically invalid; only values are allowed \\
  \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\subsection{Notes on the rewrite rules}

\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Substitution, rule \rulename{subst}.}
  \begin{itemize}
    \item \rulename{subst} does not discard the heap binding, because it may be needed,
      in \rulename{if-true} and \rulename{for}.  We could also use a rule that substitutes
     in just one place (a la Ariola)
   \item The heap always binds a variable to a \emph{value}, and values can freely
     be duplicated without duplicating work, so \rulename{subst} does not duplicate work.
   \item The side condition $x \in \freevars{e}$ is present solely to avoid \rulename{subst} being
     \emph{always} applicable, albeit vacuously.
   \end{itemize}
\item Rule \rulename{do-def}. To achieve $\freevars{e} \disjoint \boundvars{h}$, use \rulename{subst}
  to substitute out the heap bindings.  This can only get stuck if $h$ has a variable introduction |x|,
  and |x| is mentioned in |e|.  It's fine to get stuck: Verse does not
  allow a \hexp{} to return an unbound logical variable.
\item \emph{Heaps.}  ToDo: what if the heap bound a variable to an expression, like
  in the call-by-need lambda-calculus?  Would that have any merit?  I suspect not.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Unification}

Rules \rulename{uvar}-\rulename{uconst} do conventional unification, decomposing
tuples where necessary.  Notice that |e_1 == e_2| reduces to its unified value.  For example,
|(3==3) + 7| reduces to |10|.

In rule \rulename{uconst} there are two uses of ``$=$'', but they are different!  The ``|k_1 == k_2|''
on the LHS is part of the syntax of Verse, and is shorthand for |unify^(v_1,v_2)|. In contrast
the ``$k_1 = k_2$'' in the side-condition is ``real'' equality: it means that |k_1| and |k_2| are the
same constant.

Rules \rulename{B1}-\rulename{B4} come into play when variables are involved. For example
\rulename{B1} says that when |x| is in scope, \emph{and does not already have a value in the heap} (hence |H^[x]| not |H^[x := v]|),
we may unify |x| with a value |v|, and replace the unbound |x| in the heap with the bound |x := v|, thus |H^[x:=v]|.

Crucially, note that $X$ does not look inside \hexp{}s. For example |def (x) in (if(x==3) then e_1 else e_2)| does
not unify |x| via \rulename{B1}; only variables bound by the \emph{innermost enclosing \hexp{}} can be unified.
Nor does $X$ look inside choices.  For example,
|def (x) in (x==2 choice x==3)| does not unify |x| via \rulename{B1}.

Rules \rulename{B1} and \rulename{B2} includes an ``occurs check'', which ensures we never
get cycles in the heap.

\subsection{Choice and failure}

Rule \rulename{choose} is the crucial one: it duplicates the entire |def| context.  But note the
\emph{choice-free} context |CX|!  For example, the expression
$$
|def (x,y) in (x == (3 choice 4)) ; (y == (9 choice 2)); (x,y)|
$$
should yield the values |(3,9)|, |(3,2)|, |(4,9)|, |(4,2)|, in that order.
To get the order right, we must apply \rulename{choose} to the first choice |(3 choice 4)| first, and only
then to the second |(9 choice 2)|.  This is achieved by using |CX| in \rulename{choose} to ensure that only the
\emph{leftmost} choice can be chosen.

Rule \rulename{fail} collapes an entire |def| to |none| if we encounter |fail|.  It uses the |X| evaluation
context, which looks more deeply into an expression than does |CX|.  For example
$$
|def (x,y) in (x == (3 choice 4)) ; (y == (9 choice 2)); fail; (x,y)|
$$
can fail immediately; we don't need to perform the choices for |x| and |y| first, because they will all fail.
The use of |X| also means that a |def h in (2, fail plus 3, 7)| will collapse to |none| by \rulename{fail};
we do not need rules
like $|fail plus e| \movesto |fail|$.

But note that $X$ does not look inside choices.  For example, |def h in (fail choice e)| does not collapse
to |none| by \rulename{fail}.

\subsection{Functions and application}

Rule \rulename{app-lam} is a rather simple and beautiful $\beta$-reduction rule.
Notice that |apply| is one of the primitive functions in $cop$.

A tuples/array behaves like a (finite) function, and can be applied to a numeric value
in \rulename{app-arr} to index it.


\subsection{Source Verse}

In the Verse source language we do not write explicit |def|s. Instead, they are added
by a simple preprocessing step, that introduces a variable |x| in the innermost
|def| that encloses all its uses.
\simon{It's hard to say more until we say more about Source Verse.}

In the arms of a choice |e_1 choice e_2)| we add a |do (def h in e_1)| around |e_1| if
|e_1| introduces any new variables; and similarly |e_2|.
\simon{This was a nice little simplification.}

\subsection{Examples}

\begin{example}
  $$\begin{array}{rcl}
    \multicolumn{3}{l}{|def (x,y) in x==3; y==add^(x,1)|} \\
    \rulename{B1} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in 3; y==add^(x,1)| \\
    \rulename{p-seq} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(x,1)| \\
    \rulename{subst} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(3,1)| \\
    \rulename{p-add} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==4| \\
    \rulename{B1} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y:=4) in 4| \\
    \end{array}$$
\end{example}

\begin{example}
  $$\begin{array}{rcl}
    \multicolumn{3}{l}{|def (x,y) in y==add^(x,1); x==3; y|} \\
    \rulename{B1} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(x,1); 3; y| \\
    \rulename{subst} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(3,1); 3; y| \\
    \rulename{p-add} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y) in y==4; 3; y| \\
    \rulename{B1} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y:=4) in 4; 3; y| \\
    \rulename{p-seq}(twice) & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y:=4) in y| \\
    \rulename{subst} & \movesto & |def (x:=3,y:=4) in 4|
    \end{array}$$
  The evaluation of |add^(x,1)| is stuck, and hence so is the unification
  |(y==add^(x,1))|.  But the evaluation context |X| allows us to apply rule \rulename{B1}
  in the \emph{second} argument of |semi|, which gives a value to |x| in the heap.
  That allows the |add| to proceed.  So ``later'' instructions can unblock ``earlier'' ones.
\end{example}

\begin{example}
  $$\begin{array}{rcl}
    \multicolumn{3}{l}{|def (x,y) in y==add^(x,1); ((x==3) choice (x==77))|} \\
    \rulename{choose} & \movesto & |(def (x,y) in y==add^(x,1); x==3) hchoice| \\
    & & |(def (x,y) in y==add^(x,1); x==77)| \\
    \rulename{B1} (twice) & \movesto & |(def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(x,1); 3) hchoice| \\
    & & |(def (x:=77,y) in y==add^(x,1); 77)| \\
    \rulename{subst} (twice) & \movesto & |(def (x:=3,y) in y==add^(3,1); 3) hchoice| \\
    & & |(def (x:=77,y) in y==add^(77,1); 77)| \\
    \rulename{p-add} (twice) & \movesto & |(def (x:=3,y) in y==4; 3) hchoice (def (x:=77,y) in y==78; 77)| \\
    \rulename{B1}(twice) & \movesto & |(def (x:=3,y:=4) in 4; 3) hchoice (def (x:=77,y:=78) in 78; 77)| \\
    \rulename{p-seq}(twice) & \movesto & |(def (x:=3,y:=4) in 3) hchoice (def (x:=77,y:=78) in 77)| \\
    \end{array}$$
  As before, the unification |y==add^(x,1)| is stuck until we get a value for |x|.
  But this time we get two different values for |x| in the two branches of the choice.
  The crucial rule \rulename{choose} duplicates the heap and the expression that surround
  the choice, allowing execution to proceed entirely independently in the two copies.
\end{example}
